REPORT OP AUDITOR OF PUBLIC ACCOUNTS 5 • Report of State Auditor State of Nebraska AUDITOR'S OFFICE To the Honorable Adam McMullen, Governor of Nebraska. Lincoln, Nebraska. Dear Governor: — In accordance with statute 4847, I take pleasure in submitting my biennial report herewith, covering the two fiscal years of 1924-1925 und 1925-1926. The statement of Resources and Liabilities of the State, as required by statute, you will find on page 9, showing resources totaling $69,724,491.47 with no State indebtedness. This is an increase in resources of $4,647,107.45 over the figures reported six years ago. This has been my fourth term as State Auditor and looking back I am impressed with the changes that have occurred during my time increasing the activities of the state and the responsibility of its officers. Chief among these are the measures providing for the con - struction and maintenance of the state highways, the creation of the capitol commission and the building of the state capitol, the formation of the civil administration code, the expansion of the state institutions etc. The demands upon the state seem to be ever increasing and the added activities in turn cause increased state expenditures. For the biennium ending November 30th, 1920, the state cost expenditures totaled $22,637,781.70, while for the two years ending June 30th, 1926 the total was $29,714,085.52, an increase of $7,076,303.82, or about 31 per cent. This includes the expenditures from Federal and Cash Funds and the distribution of the trust funds such as the temporary school fund. I am unable to give comparisons on basis of the earlier years, meaning the year prior to my time, since former accountants have failed to prepare recapitulations of the total expenditures to be em - bodied in the auditor's biennial reports, in fact they do not seem to have considered it necessary to report on the Federal Funds and all the cash funds. Similarly their statements of the appropriations are incomplete and no fair comparisons can be made as against these prior years.

6 An effort has been made during my term of office to classify the accounts, pertaining to state receipts and expenditures and I refer to the comparative statement on page 42 of this report. By separately grouping the expenditures for capitol outlay and public improvement, and the distribution of the trust funds, the ordinary cost of running the state is set out for each year. It will be noted that there has been a steady increase in the government cost. Only the expenditures for capitol outlay show great fluctuations. Capitol outlay includes public improvements such as roads and bridges, construction of new buildings. purchase of bonds for the soldiers relief fund etc. It is in the expendi- tures for capitol outlay where "Savings" or to be more exact, post- ponement of expenditures have been made during certain years. The increased activities of the state have greatly added to the duties and the work to be performed by the state auditor's de- partment. This is readily seen by comparing the number of vouchers audited and warrants issued. Warrants issued each month 1921 1926 Month of April 6,098 9,974 Month of May 7,364 10,574 Month of June 7,580 10,011 Month of July 6,641 11,125 Thus the number of warrants issued monthly have increased during my time nearly 50 per cent. There has been no increase in the appro- priations since 1921 as shown by the following: Appropriated for 1921 1926 Salary State Auditor $10,000.00 $10,000.00 Salary Deputy Auditor 5,280.00 5,280.00 Salaries and Wages 31,120.00 31,120.00 Maintenance 9,000.00 9,000.00 Receipts from Metropolitan. Water District Omaha Estimate Estimate Total from Tax Funds $55,400.00 $55,400.00 It has been a source of great satisfaction to me that it has been possible to take care of this increased work without additional cost to the state. This has been accomplished by assembling an efficient office force, each one of whom has labored faithfully to perform the allotted tasks. I would say, however, that the limit of what is possible has about been reached if not exceeded and I have considered it necessary to ask for an increase of appropriations for the benefit of my successor. My first biennial report showed bonds registered amounting to $22,124,089.52. During the two years covered by this report, the amount was $30,341,373.00, an increase of $8,217,283.48 or about 37 per cent. The increase comes mostly from the school districts as shown by the following

7 The counties are the only division that show a decrease. The amount of school district bonds registred has just doubled. And now that I come to the end of my eighth year as State Auditor, I want to express my appreciation of the confidence shown in me by the people of this state in honoring me by repeatedly re-electing me. I have enjoyed the friendship and good will of the various state officers and employees and am retiring with the belief that the work of my department has been satisfactory. Great credit is due to the members of my office force who have assisted me in keeping up the records, ready for public inspection at any time. Respectfully submitted GEORGE W. MARSH, State Auditor.
